<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-338-021  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 338 021.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  Feb 1989 v109 n2 p40(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Full-text retrieval: what it is and what it can do: faster,cheaper CPUs and storage, and far better input devices are drivingsoftware down to micros.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gabrielson, Heidi.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Full-text retrieval capability in a data base environment meansthat a user can free-form search-and-retrieve any word or wordstring from a text data base or a collection of documents.andO;Text-retrieval software, used on mainframes and on-line systemsfor many years, has a reputation for being slow, expensive anddifficult to use.andP;  Faster, less expensive CPUs and storage arechanging the situation, driving software down to microcomputers.andO;Text retrieval software for a microcomputer ranges from $50 to$995.andP;  Basically, three retrieval methods are involved: invertedindex or keyword; character string search or pattern matching; andintelligent or relevant searches.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Text Data BasesFree-Text SearchingOn-Line SearchingMicrocomputersSoftware PackagesTrendsIndustry Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>